Pronunciation[edit]

  • (Classical) IPA(key): /ˈin.troː/, [ˈɪn̪.t̪ɾoː]
  • (Ecclesiastical) IPA(key): /ˈin.tro/, [ˈin̪.t̪rɔ]

Etymology 1[edit]

From intrā (“within”).

Verb[edit]

intrō (present infinitive intrāre, perfect active intrāvī, supine intrātum); first conjugation

  1. I enter, go into, penetrate.

Descendants[edit]
  • Aromanian: ãntru, intru
  • intrāre (present active infinitive)
    • Romanian: intra, întra
    • Italo-Dalmatian
      • Corsican: entra
      • Dalmatian: entrur
      • Italian: intrare, entrare
    • Old French: entrer
      • Middle French: entrer
        • French: entrer
      • Norman: entrer
      • → Middle English: entren
        • English: enter
        • Scots: enter
    • Old Occitan: entrar, intrar
      • Catalan: entrar
      • Occitan: intrar, entrar
      • ⇒ Occitan: dintrar
    • Rhaeto-Romance
      • Friulian: jentrâ
      • Romansch: entrar, antrar, entrer
    • Sardinian: intràe, intrai, intrare
    • Venetian: entrar
    • West Iberian
      • Asturian: entrar
      • Old Portuguese: intrar, entrar
        • Galician: entrar
        • Portuguese: entrar
      • Old Spanish: [Term?]
        • Ladino: entrar
        • Spanish: entrar (see there for further descendants)
  • ⇒ Irish: iontráil

Etymology 2[edit]

Same as intrā.

Preposition[edit]

intrō

  1. within
Derived terms[edit]
  • intrōrsum
Descendants[edit]
  • Eastern Romance
    • Aromanian: tru
    • Romanian: întru
  • Italian: entro
  • Spanish: entro
  • ⇒ Old Portuguese: dentro
    • Portuguese: dentro
  • → English: enter
